SIMPLE: subcontrary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Subcontrary
<hw>Sub*con"tra*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Contrary in an inferior degree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>Having, or being in, a contrary
order; -- said of a section of an oblique cone having a circular base
made by a plane not parallel to the base, but so inclined to the axis
that the section is a circle; applied also to two similar triangles when
so placed as to have a common angle at the vertex, the opposite sides
not being parallel.</def> <rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>Denoting the relation of
opposition between the <xex>particular affirmative</xex> and
<xex>particular negative</xex>. Of these both may be true and only one
can be false.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subcontrary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Subcontrary
<hw>Sub*con"tra*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Subcontraries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>A
subcontrary proposition; a proposition inferior or contrary in a lower
degree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subcoracoid</ent>⟦br⟧
